(Main Lesson) Tj
T*
(1. Introduction To The Topic) Tj
T*
(Figures of speech create imagery, emphasis, and style in language. In a textbook lesson,) Tj
T*
(the first goal is to make the language idea clear. Students should be able to explain) Tj
T*
(what Figures of Speech means, identify where it appears in English, and describe the) Tj
T*
(main purpose of the topic without relying on memorized sentences.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2. Core Teaching) Tj
T*
(The central focus in Figures of Speech is metaphor, simile, personification, hyperbole,) Tj
T*
(and effect. This means students must move beyond the overview and understand how the) Tj
T*
(idea actually works. A strong explanation should unpack the rules, relationships, or) Tj
T*
(patterns behind Figures of Speech and show how those ideas guide correct answers. In) Tj
T*
(English, success usually depends on understanding the meaning, form, and effect that) Tj
T*
(belong to the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. How The Idea Is Applied) Tj
T*
(A useful way to teach Figures of Speech is to connect the explanation directly to) Tj
T*
(explaining the effect of a metaphor in a sentence. That kind of language example shows) Tj
T*
(students how the topic moves from theory into use. At this stage, the learner should be) Tj
T*
(able to state the relevant rule or principle, explain why it fits the question, and then) Tj
T*
(apply the interpretation or writing method with confidence.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. Why Errors Happen) Tj
T*
(One common difficulty in Figures of Speech is spotting a figure of speech without) Tj
T*
(describing its effect. This matters because many learners can repeat a definition but) Tj
T*
